-- 
Hong Kong Stocks Rise as Commodity Shares Gain on Oil, Metals

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-05-26T08:33:37Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-26/hong-kong-stocks-rise-as-commodity-shares-gain-on-oil-metals.html
Hong Kong’s  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  rose for
a third straight day as commodity shares advanced after oil and
metal prices increased.  Cnooc Ltd. (883) ,  China ’s biggest offshore oil producer, gained
2.9 percent, the steepest gain in the Hang Seng Index. Aluminum
Corp. of China Ltd., the country’s largest producer of the
lightweight metal, rose 0.9 percent, and Jiangxi Copper Co.,
China’s No. 1 producer of the metal, advanced 1.6 percent.  China
Eastern  Airlines Corp. gained 3.6 percent after a report said
the nation’s carriers can increase fuel surcharges on domestic
routes longer than 800 kilometers (500 miles).  The Hang Seng Index rose 0.7 percent to 22,900.79 at the
close, with three stocks rising for each that fell on the 45-
member gauge. The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index of Chinese
companies’ H shares climbed 0.5 percent to 12,752.08.  “It’s a bit of a mixed bag at the moment, without an
overall trend,” said  Andrew Sullivan , director of institutional
sales trading at OSK Securities Hong Kong Ltd. “It’s a slightly
rotational market today where people are looking at sectors.
People are looking at the bright side of the news today.”  Cnooc rose 2.9 percent to HK$18.68, the second-biggest
contributor to the Hang Seng Index’s advance.  China Petroleum &
Chemical Corp. (386) ,  Asia ’s largest oil refiner known as Sinopec,
gained 1.5 percent to HK$7.50. Aluminum Corp. of China increased
0.9 percent to HK$6.59, while Jiangxi Copper advanced 1.6
percent to HK$25.45.  Commodities Advance  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index gained 0.3
percent today. In  New York , the index gained 0.3 percent
yesterday as commodity shares rallied on expectations for higher
raw material prices.  Crude oil for July delivery rose 1.7 percent to $101.32 a
barrel in New York yesterday, the highest settlement since May
10, as a report showed that U.S. inventories of diesel and
heating oil tumbled to the lowest level in more than two years
with increased consumption.  Copper futures for July delivery jumped 2.3 percent in New
York yesterday, the biggest gain since May 18, as Deutsche Bank
AG said prices will probably climb. The London Metal Exchange
Index of six metals, including copper and aluminum, rose 2.1
percent yesterday.  Some airlines gained on speculation profit will increase on
higher fuel surcharges. China Eastern, the nation’s No. 2
carrier by passenger numbers, rose 3.6 percent to HK$3.50.  Air
China Ltd. (601111) , the country’s biggest international carrier,
advanced 1.2 percent to HK$7.87.  Airlines Gain  China’s airlines can raise fuel surcharges on domestic
routes longer than 800 kilometers to 140 yuan ($22) from 90 yuan
from today, Shanghai Daily said, citing the National Development
and Reform Commission.  The Hang Seng Index has fallen 1.3 percent this year
through yesterday amid concern  Europe ’s debt crisis and China’s
tightening measures will slow global economic growth. Shares in
the gauge traded at an average 12.1 times forecast earnings
yesterday, compared with 14.4 times at the end of last year,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Among stocks that fell, Chaoda Modern Agriculture
(Holdings) Ltd., a mainland China vegetable producer, tumbled 22
percent to HK$3.62, the steepest drop in the Hang Seng Composite
Index. The company overstated the area of its farm land in
Beijing and the Chinese province of Hebei, Next Magazine
reported today, citing managers at the production bases. The
company said the report isn’t accurate, according to a statement
to the  Hong Kong  stock exchange today.  Futures on the Hang Seng Index gained 0.5 percent to
22,865. The HSI Volatility Index, the benchmark gauge for Hong
Kong stock options, fell 6.6 percent to 17.88, indicating
options traders expect a swing of 5.1 percent in the Hang Seng
Index in the next 30 days.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 